{{Infobox artwork | image_file=Menin Gate at midnight (Will Longstaff).jpg | backcolor=#FBF5DF | painting_alignment=right | image_size=300px | title=Menin Gate at Midnight | artist=[[Will Longstaff]] | year=[[1927 in art|1927]] | medium=oil on canvas | height_metric=137 | width_metric=170 | height_imperial= | width_imperial= | metric_unit=cm | imperial_unit=in | city=[[Canberra]] | museum=[[Australian War Memorial]] }} '''''Menin Gate at Midnight''''' (also known as '''''Ghosts of Menin Gate''''') is a [[1927 in art|1927]] painting by Australian artist [[Will Longstaff]]. The painting depicts a host of ghostly soldiers marching across a field in front of the [[Menin Gate]] war memorial.<ref name="AWMEncyclopedia">{{cite web|last=Grey|first=Anne|title=Menin Gate at Midnigh|url=https://www.awm.gov.au/articles/encyclopedia/menin|accessdate=1 August 2018}}</ref> The painting is part of the collection of the [[Australian War Memorial]] in [[Canberra]].<ref name="AWM Collection">{{cite web|title=ART09807 - Menin Gate at midnight|url=http://cas.awm.gov.au/item/ART09807|publisher=Australian War Memorial|accessdate=21 October 2010|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100630152957/http://cas.awm.gov.au/item/ART09807|archivedate=30 June 2010|df=}}</ref>
Longstaff painted the work after attending the unveiling of the Menin Gate memorial, at [[Ypres]] in Belgium, on 24 July 1927. The memorial commemorated those men of the [[British Empire]], including Australia, who died in the battles of the [[First World War]] around the town.<ref name=AWMEncyclopedia /> Walking around the streets of Ypres after the ceremony, Longstaff was said to have seen a "vision of steel-helmeted spirits rising from the moonlit cornfields around him".<ref name=AWMEncyclopedia /> Returning to London, Longstaff was reported to have painted the work in a single session, while "still under psychic influence".<ref name=AWMEncyclopedia />
The painting was immediately popular. It was purchased by [[Lord Woolavington]] for 2,000 [[Guinea (British coin)|Guinea]]s and presented to the Australian government.<ref name=AWMEncyclopedia /> After a royal command viewing for [[George V]] and the Royal family at Buckingham Palace, the painting was displayed in Manchester and Glasgow. It was then taken around Australia, where record crowds paid to view the work. Longstaff oversaw the making of 2,000 prints and 400 of these were given to the nascent [[Australian War Memorial]] to sell to raise funds.<ref name=AWMEncyclopedia />
The success of this work lead Longstaff to paint three later companion pieces with a similar ghostly, spiritualist theme:<ref name=AWMEncyclopedia /> *''Immortal Shrine (Eternal Silence)'' &ndash; showing ghostly soldiers marching past the [[Cenotaph#The Cenotaph, London|Cenotaph]] in London on [[Remembrance Day]] *''Ghosts of Vimy Ridge'' (1931) &ndash; depicting men of the [[Canadian Corps]] at [[Vimy Ridge]]. *''Carillon'' (1932) &ndash; with New Zealand soldiers in Belgium hearing the bells in their native country.
